  "opinion": "As a mechanic in Milan with three children and a background that doesn't include advanced education beyond lower secondary, I've seen firsthand how stereotypes about STEM fields can create real barriers. Stereotype threat isn't just a theoretical concept—it's the anxiety that comes when someone feels their group is labeled as less capable in a particular field. For example, when my daughter, who's interested in engineering, starts school, she sometimes hesitates to ask questions because she worries her teachers might think she's 'not smart enough.' This isn't just about girls—it's about anyone who feels their identity might be judged in a technical context. In my community, where many people have limited formal education, the idea that 'only smart people can do math' can be intimidating. But addressing this isn't about changing the system overnight. It's about creating spaces where everyone feels safe to try. As a mother who values education for my children but understands that learning isn't always about being perfect, I believe we should focus on practical, hands-on learning that shows STEM isn't just for those who already know a lot. For instance, fixing a car or building something simple can be a great way to engage without the pressure of academic tests. In Milan, where there's a mix of cultures and backgrounds, it's important to emphasize that everyone has value in their own way—whether they're fixing engines or designing apps. The key is to make sure that when someone feels like they belong, they can succeed without fear. Stereotype threat is real, but it doesn't have to define the future of our children.",
